<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Jerry Hicks 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 COLOR IT BIG: The lineup for July's Orange County Fair includes more 
superstars than ever (F26). More variety too. It opens with Color Me Badd on 
July 8 and ends with Crystal Gayle on July 22. . . . In between are people like 
pianist-TV host John Tesh, the Neville Brothers, rapper Queen Latifah and 
country's Restless Heart. This year, all acts are at the Pacific Amphitheatre. 
Says spokeswoman Jill Lloyd: "We've spent more money this year trying to 
provide more top entertainment." 
</P>
<P>
 ANOTHER LOOK: The family of Gloria Ramirez, who died at Riverside General 
Hospital in February on the same night that mysterious fumes forced evacuation 
of its emergency room, has hired forensic pathologist Richard Fukumoto of 
Orange County to conduct a private autopsy today, now that her body has been 
released to them (A3). Fukumoto is a veteran of the autopsy table. He has 
performed thousands of autopsies for the county since the early '60s. Deputy 
Dist. Atty. Bryan Brown has said of him: "We're blessed in this county, but 
Fukumoto is just the best there is." 
</P>
<P>
 CODY'S MOVIE: A funny thing happened when Madison Allen of Laguna Niguel 
boarded his 1-year-old wolf-hybrid dog Cody at a friend's kennel in Corona last 
year: Cody got discovered. Producers wanted him for "White Fang 2" -- a sequel 
-- which opens at 20 theaters in Orange County today (F6). . . . Allen, a 
22-year-old Saddleback College student, says he loved being on the movie set in 
Canada last year: "Cody loved it too. They train by food reward, and he got to 
eat all the time." 
</P>
<P>
 RED FLAGS: If you see someone at work wearing a red plastic nose today, it has 
nothing to do with this being deadline day for taxes. Red Nose Day USA is to 
call attention to sudden infant death syndrome. . . . Booster Leighann Faley of 
Mission Viejo has been raising funds selling those noses -- and badges that say 
"I'm too chicken to wear a red nose." Says Faley: "You're going to see red 
noses all over Orange County today." 
</P>
