<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VALLEY FOCUS: VAN NUYS; ARRAIGNMENT DELAYED FOR JACK NICHOLSON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By THOM MROZEK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 An arraignment for Jack Nicholson, who is charged with attacking a 
Mercedes-Benz with a golf club, was delayed for a second time Thursday so his 
attorney could continue working on a deal that would effectively dismiss the 
charges, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
 Appearing in Van Nuys Municipal Court without the Oscar-winning actor, defense 
attorney Charles R. English was allowed to put off the arraignment until April 
26, saying he was trying to arrange a meeting between Nicholson and the driver 
of the Mercedes, according to Deputy City Atty. Jeff Harkavy. 
</P>
<P>
 Nicholson is charged with misdemeanor counts of assault and vandalism for 
allegedly using a 3-iron to smash the windshield and roof of Robert Scott 
Blank's car. Blank, a 38-year-old Hollywood resident, was near the intersection 
of Moorpark Way and Riverside Drive in Toluca Lake when the Feb. 8 incident 
occurred. Prosecutors have said Nicholson may have believed that Blank cut him 
off in traffic. 
</P>
<P>
 Blank subsequently filed a lawsuit against Nicholson, but the matter has been 
settled for an undisclosed sum. 
</P>
<P>
 Nicholson is reportedly seeking a "civil compromise" in the criminal action. 
California law allows a judge to permanently stay misdemeanor criminal actions 
if the victim receives compensation in civil court. 
</P>
<P>
 A civil compromise effectively dismisses the charges in a case and prevents 
authorities from later prosecuting. 
</P>
<P>
 English refused to confirm that he is actively seeking a civil compromise, but 
the attorney acknowledged "that is one of the possible resolutions to the case 
given that Mr. Nicholson and Mr. Blank have settled their civil differences." 
</P>
<P>
 Stressing that he is not trying to single out Nicholson, Harkavy said that 
"due to the degree of violence," his office strenuously opposes this type of 
settlement. 
</P>
<P>
 "This case went beyond property damage," Harkavy said. "As alleged in the 
complaint, Mr. Nicholson assaulted the victim, and he suffered some minor 
injuries." 
</P>
<P>
 The prosecutor said the golf club shattered Blank's windshield and several 
small pieces of glass struck his face. THOM MROZEK 
</P>
</TEXT>
